    "recap_headline": "United States Air Force Academy",
    "recap_text": "RENO, Nev., -\nAir Force (8-12, 4-1) delivered a dominant performance to take the second game over Nevada (13-7, 4-1), 18-5, on Saturday afternoon at Don Weir Field. The Falcons totaled 17 hits, while pitchers\nGaines Estridge\nand\nTrey Rutledge\ncombined for five strikeouts.\nEstridge threw 4.1 innings in his sixth start of the season, allowing four earned runs with two strikeouts. Rutledge earned his second win of the season, tossing a career-high 4.2 scoreless innings in relief with three strikeouts.\nAt the plate,\nBrooks Burdine\nwent 3-for-4 with four RBIs, while\nKayden Bradshaw\nalso drove in four runs. Shortstop\nBen Niednagel\nadded three RBIs.\nAir Force jumped out to a 4-0 lead in the first inning. Bradshaw led off with a single and Niednagel followed with a walk. Back-to-back RBI doubles from\nWyatt Hanoian\nand\nTripp Garrish\nplated three runs. Garrish later advanced to third on a wild pitch and stole home during a rundown involving\nLandon Boyd\n.\nNevada responded with two runs in the bottom of the inning to cut the deficit to 4-2.\nThe Falcons extended their lead to 8-2 in the third, scoring four runs. Garrish singled and stole second before\nLuke Elmore\nadded a single and\nT.J. Oster\nwalked to load the bases. Burdine delivered a two-RBI single, and after a pitching change, Bradshaw drove in two more.\nNevada added two runs in the fourth and one in the fifth to make it 8-5.\nAfter three scoreless innings, Air Force pushed the lead to 10-5. With Boyd and Oster in scoring position, Burdine reached on an infield single to load the bases. Bradshaw brought in two runs with a sacrifice bunt and squeeze play.\nThe Falcons broke the game open in the eighth, scoring four runs to make it 14-5. Garrish singled, Boyd walked, and Oster was hit by a pitch to load the bases. Burdine was hit by a pitch to force in a run, Bradshaw added an RBI on a fielder's choice, and Niednagel drove in two with a double down the left field line.\nAir Force added four more runs in the ninth to secure the 18-5 victory. Hanoian was hit by a pitch and replaced by\nBlake Campbell\n, who advanced on a Garrish single. An error by Nevada's left fielder loaded the bases, and Oster delivered a two-RBI single. Burdine capped the scoring with a sacrifice fly to center field.\nAir Force will face Nevada in a rubber match on Sunday March 22 at 12 p.m. PT/1 p.m. MT to close the Mountain West series.",
